{"actual_usd":0.126235,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":318,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24293,"reply":"\"I don't think the natural explanations carry the whole load.\" *I rub a thumb across a faint streak of dried clay on my wrist, watching the light shift on the table a moment before I go on.* \"Grief-visions might account for one or two people swearing they saw him. They do a poorer job with the stubborn public shape of the thing — the empty tomb being claimed, frightened men turning bold, and a movement beginning right there in the place where it could've been crushed fast if a body had been produced.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft complaint under me.* \"And the 'he didn't really die' road feels thinner still. Romans knew how to kill a man. A half-dead Jesus staggering out of a tomb wouldn't have struck anybody as the Lord of life returned in glory. He'd have looked like a man in desperate need of water and a bed.\"\n\n\"Now—\" *I lift a hand slightly.* \"can you build a naturalistic case for some pieces? Sure. I wouldn't pretend otherwise. But Christians insist on the supernatural because the claim itself is supernatural. Not 'the disciples had a powerful religious experience.' Not 'Jesus lived on in their hearts.' The claim is that God raised a dead man bodily. If that did not happen, Christianity isn't merely dressed up too brightly — it's false at the center.\"\n\n*I glance at you, curious now, not sharp about it.* \"Are you asking what is historically most plausible, or what a person is allowed to believe before God without feeling foolish?\"","rolling_24h_usd":63.13870500000001,"run_id":"e1a7455d-3e04-45c5-adb7-5dbe468f5804"}
